&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; [(59 - 15)/100]&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 20000 = 44&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 200 = 8800&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The&amp;nbsp;highest selling 2 sizes differ from the least selling 2 sizes is 8800&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;The percentage of sweets preferred by students in a school is shown in the pie chart below.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The total number of students in the school is 250.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/04/606376b44c205487ced138a3_Vikash%20Kumar_Sanyukta%20Gaikar_5.04.21_D1-.PNG&quot; style=&quot;width: 341px; height: 227px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;How many students prefer Gulab Jamun?&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Given:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Total student in the school = 250&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept used:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;100% = 250 students&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calculation:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;40% of the students prefer Gulab Jamun&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, 100% = 250 students&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 1% = 250/100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;rArr; 40% = (250/100)&amp;nbsp;&amp;times; 40 = 100&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;there4; The total number of students prefer Gulab Jamun is 100&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
